query.result:
1 Only the world believed in its peril 2 that the beautiful Cyprigna, the foolish love 3 shone, turned in the third epicycle;
4 because not only to her did the ancient people 5 in the ancient error do honor 6 with sacrifice and with votive cry;
7 but they honored Dione and Cupid, 8 that one as his mother, this one as her son, 9 and they said that he sat in Dido's lap;
10 and from this one from whom I take my beginning 11 they took the name of the star 12 that the sun courts now from the cup now from the brow.

13 I did not notice the ascent into it;
14 but my lady whom I saw become more beautiful
15 gave me ample proof that I was inside it.

22 From a cold cloud no winds descended, 23 visible or not, so swift, 24 that they would not have seemed impeded and slow
25 to one who had seen those divine lights 26 coming toward us, leaving the circle 27 first begun among the high Seraphim;
28 and within those that appeared in front 29 resounded ‘Hosanna’ so that never after 30 was I without the desire to hear it again.

55 You loved me greatly, and you had good reason;
56 for if I had remained down there, I would have shown you
57 more of my love than just the leaves.

